<br>
As for your father smacking your sister, I'm glad he was upset he did it.  He did it out of anger, and that was wrong.<br>
<br>
And I agree with Sseti's first point on page 7 (and strongly disagree that teaching children about God equates to ignorance).  The decline in CP is a general symptom of the general parenting theories that go along with it, and which I believe are the more serious culprits for the decline in discipline amongst the emerging generations.  It's not just that parents are spanking their children, they aren't disciplining them in any way.  &quot;Kids will be kids...&quot; is a far too common statement by parents.  <br>
<br>
I watched some twerp dad on Father's Day at the park trying to teach his three year old to ride a bike - without training wheels.  [I was there with my boys on their bikes - with training wheels.]  Aside from the sheer idiocy of that (my very physical 4 year old boys aren't remotely coordinated enough to ride a bike) methodology, his parenting skills were atrocious.  First, the kid had a helmet, but didn't want to wear it, so the dad said okay.  Bzzzzt - wrong answer, Chump!  (And boy was he offended when I politely suggested that his kid ought to be wearing a helmet like the 20 other kids at the park.)  Second, he was doing nothing but berating the poor kid when he fell.  Third, when the kids 6 year old sister tried to help and the 3 yr old struck her, and she hit back, the dad said nothing.  What an idiot!<br>
<br>
The problem I see with parents all the time is that they want to be their kid's friend, not their parent.  So they avoid discipline and correction at all costs.  First, that's a parents job.  Second, it's a friend's job, too.  Third, if you aren't going to discipline your children, you have no room to complain about how unlucky you were that your kids turned out crappy, or that I got lucky that my kids are fabulous. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ucarathosollathir.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Carathos Ollathir</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalRainbow.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 1779<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/18/02 2:03:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3406.topic&index=148>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Parenting</span><hr size=1> Well, I don't know how he does it, but I have a friend with a boy 3 years old that can ride a bike better that I could twice his age (no training wheels).  He just zooms around the yard and driveway just as easy as you please.  Shocked the hell out of me <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>Carathos Ollathir<br>
