<br>
On the other hand, I fully agree that poor parenting is responsible for a lot of the social problems we see. &quot;Proper family values&quot;, and better disipline would make a big difference to this. Physical violence towards children could be used to help instill discipline and family values. However, I believe it can do great harm if used excessively. Possibly it also does not-so-great-but-not-insignificant harm if used less excessivly. I don't think it's currently clear, if at all possible to determine, the extent or nature of any such &quot;lesser&quot; harm, caused by minimal phyisical punshiment, and given that I believe there are other alternatives, I find them preferable.<br>
<br>
An example of a &quot;lesser&quot; harm: Most(?) children who have experienced corporal punshiment consider it much more acceptable than those who weren't. If this extends to seeing violence as a more acceptable solution to problems in general, then I see corporal punishment as harmful, in that it is encouraging a viewpoint which I consider harmful to society. Even proporaging the idea that violence towards children in some situations (corporal punshiment as a form of discipline) is OK isn't something I feel comfortable with. Clearly, indulgent parents who let kids get away with anything (in particular violent actions) are teaching the same &quot;violence is OK&quot; lesson. Correcting that kind of behaviour has to be done to be a responsible parent, however, I don't accept the only way to correct a child's behaviour is to hit them. <p>----------------------------------<br>
[59 Troubadour]
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=78662">Maeri</a>
&lt;Anlah'Shok&gt;</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uraedwulf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Raedwulf</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_thatch.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 1185<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/19/02 12:40:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3406.topic&index=152>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Parenting</span><hr size=1> Upon what basis have you decided that the correlation between a lack of parental discipline and crime stats is lesser than the correlation between corporal punishment and criminal conduct/depression?  My own conclusion is exactly the opposite.<br>
<br>
Juvenile crime/poor behaviour is a directly related pattern compared to parental discipline.  Kids act bad because parents let them.  Whereas violent crime has dozens of major causes outside abusive parenting:  poverty, drug abuse, gangs, lack of economic mobility, etc.<br>
<br>
I agree with you that corporal punishment &quot;if used excessively&quot; can be abusive and do great harm.  However, that's not my proposition.  As I said, CP if used in anger or to excess, is neither appropriate nor ultimately beneficial.  It's also not the first response used.<br>
<br>
What are the alternatives to communicating with a 1-3 year old?  Reason?  Nope.  Tying them down so they can't get near a source of danger/restriction/limit?  Nope.  [I have twin boys.  When they were young, they bit one another.  Was I supposed to keep them from interacting at any time?  No way, and now they are best friends.  A good swat on the bottom worked wonders to remind them that biting was not acceptable.  Nothing else worked.]  There are alternatives, but they occasionally don't work.  Loving, consistent, limited corporal punishment is an effective and appropriate tool of teaching a child self-discipline. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uchiteng.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Chiteng</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 1209<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/19/02 3:02:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3406.topic&index=153>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Parenting</span><hr size=1> I am forced to agree with Heinlein on this one. Excessive permissivness only feeds<br>
